{
  "master": {
    "tasks": [
      {
        "id": "1",
        "title": "Create and switch to 'updates' branch",
        "description": "Create a new git branch called 'updates' off of main, switch to it, and verify the working tree is clean before any changes are made.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "This is a gate task - NO other task may begin until this one is complete and verified. Steps:\n\n1. Verify current state: run `git status` - working tree must be clean. If not, stash or commit first.\n2. Fetch latest: `git fetch origin`\n3. Verify you're on main and up to date: `git checkout main && git pull origin main`\n4. Create and switch to the new branch: `git checkout -b updates`\n5. Verify the switch: `git branch --show-current` must print exactly `updates`\n6. Push the branch to origin to establish tracking: `git push -u origin updates`\n\nBEFORE STARTING ANY SUBSEQUENT TASK: run `git branch --show-current` and confirm it returns `updates`. If it returns anything else, STOP and switch back with `git checkout updates`.\n\nSuperpowers note: The `using-git-worktrees` skill is an alternative to a single branch if you want parallel task execution - you can create a worktree per major task group (schema, security, docker, dashboard). For this remediation, a single branch is simpler and the plan assumes that.",
        "testStrategy": "Run `git branch --show-current` and verify output is `updates`. Run `git status` and verify 'nothing to commit, working tree clean'. Run `git log --oneline -1` and verify the HEAD matches origin/main at the point of branching.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T00:45:32.369Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "2",
        "title": "Delete stray am4_data.db.N file and update .gitignore",
        "description": "Remove the committed SQLite artifact at repo root and extend .gitignore to prevent similar files from being tracked in future.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-19, and the .gitignore pattern `*.db` does not match `am4_data.db.N`.\n\nSteps:\n1. Delete the file: `git rm am4_data.db.N`\n2. Open `.gitignore` and change the Data section from:\n   ```\n   # Data\n   *.db\n   *.sqlite\n   *.parquet\n   ```\n   to:\n   ```\n   # Data\n   *.db\n   *.db-*\n   *.db.*\n   *.sqlite\n   *.sqlite-*\n   *.parquet\n   ```\n   This catches WAL files (*.db-wal), shared memory files (*.db-shm), backup variants (*.db.bak), and the am4_data.db.N stray.\n3. Commit: `git add .gitignore && git commit -m \"chore: remove stray am4_data.db.N and tighten db gitignore\"`\n\nNote: If the file ever contained real extraction data, it is now permanently in git history. Consider `git filter-repo` in a follow-up task if that matters; for a public repo with a game-data DB, the exposure is minimal.",
        "testStrategy": "Run `ls am4_data.db.N 2>/dev/null` - should return nothing. Run `git check-ignore -v am4_data.db.N am4_data.db-wal am4_data.db.bak` - each should match a line in .gitignore. Run `git status` - working tree clean after commit.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T00:56:05.658Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "3",
        "title": "Exclude .env, .env.*, and .mcp.json from Docker builds",
        "description": "Fix SEC-07 and SEC-08 - secrets files are currently copied into the Docker image via COPY . .",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-07 (.env not in .dockerignore), SEC-08 (.mcp.json tracked in git and not dockerignored).\n\nCurrent .dockerignore is 15 lines and excludes .venv, __pycache__, *.db, .git/, etc. but does NOT exclude .env or .mcp.json. Since the Dockerfile does `COPY . .`, any .env or .mcp.json with real API keys ends up baked into the image layer.\n\nSteps:\n1. Edit `.dockerignore` and add these lines:\n   ```\n   # Secrets\n   .env\n   .env.*\n   !.env.example\n   .mcp.json\n   !.mcp.json.example\n   ```\n   The `!.env.example` and `!.mcp.json.example` negations preserve the example files so new contributors still have templates.\n\n2. Rename the tracked .mcp.json to .mcp.json.example (the current file has placeholder values so this is a pure rename):\n   ```\n   git mv .mcp.json .mcp.json.example\n   ```\n\n3. Add .mcp.json to .gitignore (the untracked real-keys version). In .gitignore, under the `# Environment variables` section, change:\n   ```\n   .env\n   ```\n   to:\n   ```\n   .env\n   .mcp.json\n   ```\n\n4. Commit: `git add .dockerignore .gitignore .mcp.json.example && git commit -m \"security: exclude .env and .mcp.json from docker and git\"`\n\n5. Update the README or CLAUDE.md briefly to note: \"Copy .mcp.json.example to .mcp.json and fill in API keys - the real file is gitignored.\"",
        "testStrategy": "Run `git check-ignore -v .env .mcp.json` - both should match lines in .gitignore. Run `docker build -t am4-audit-test .` and then `docker run --rm am4-audit-test ls -la /app/.env /app/.mcp.json 2>&1` - both should report 'No such file or directory'. Confirm `.mcp.json.example` is still present in the image.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T00:57:24.808Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "4",
        "title": "Fix Dockerfile double-install of am4 and pin to commit hash",
        "description": "Fix SEC-16 (branch-name pin) and the high-severity functional bug where Dockerfile installs am4 from abc8747/am4@master then requirements.txt tries to install saqibj/am4@msvc-fix.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: Dockerfile double-install bug (from first-pass audit), SEC-16 (branch pin instead of commit hash).\n\nCurrent Dockerfile lines 12-15:\n```dockerfile\nRUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip \\\n    && pip install --no-cache-dir \"am4 @ git+https://github.com/abc8747/am4.git@master\" \\\n    && pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt\n```\n\nThis: (a) wastes a full ~2-minute C++ compile installing upstream am4, then (b) may or may not reinstall from the saqibj/am4@msvc-fix URL in requirements.txt depending on pip's resolver behavior with direct URL refs. At best it double-compiles; at worst the wrong fork wins.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Find the current HEAD commit of saqibj/am4 msvc-fix branch:\n   ```\n   git ls-remote https://github.com/saqibj/am4.git refs/heads/msvc-fix\n   ```\n   Copy the full 40-character SHA.\n\n2. Update `requirements.txt` line 1 from:\n   ```\n   am4 @ git+https://github.com/saqibj/am4.git@msvc-fix\n   ```\n   to:\n   ```\n   am4 @ git+https://github.com/saqibj/am4.git@<FULL_SHA_HERE>\n   ```\n\n3. Update `pyproject.toml` line 8 to match exactly.\n\n4. Update `Dockerfile` - DELETE the explicit am4 install line. New version:\n   ```dockerfile\n   FROM python:3.12-slim\n\n   RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \\\n       build-essential cmake git \\\n       && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n   WORKDIR /app\n\n   COPY requirements.txt .\n   RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip \\\n       && pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt\n\n   COPY . .\n\n   EXPOSE 8000\n   CMD [\"python\", \"main.py\", \"dashboard\"]\n   ```\n\n5. Add a comment to requirements.txt above the am4 line documenting what the pin represents:\n   ```\n   # am4: pinned to commit hash (not branch) for reproducible builds.\n   # To upgrade: git ls-remote https://github.com/saqibj/am4.git refs/heads/msvc-fix\n   # and update both requirements.txt and pyproject.toml.\n   ```\n\n6. Commit: `git add Dockerfile requirements.txt pyproject.toml && git commit -m \"fix: single am4 install in docker, pin to commit hash\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `docker build -t am4-audit-test .` - build should succeed and am4 should compile exactly once (grep the build log for 'Building wheel for am4' and confirm only one occurrence). Run `docker run --rm am4-audit-test python -c \"from am4.utils.db import init; init(); from am4.utils.aircraft import Aircraft; print(Aircraft.search('b738').ac.name)\"` - should print `B737-800`. Run `docker run --rm am4-audit-test pip show am4 | grep Home-page` - should show saqibj/am4.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:07:00.336Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "5",
        "title": "Default dashboard --host to 127.0.0.1 and make --reload opt-in",
        "description": "Fix SEC-01 (zero auth on network-exposed server) by binding to localhost by default. Fix SEC-20 (unconditional uvicorn reload).",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-01, SEC-20. Current `main.py` line 110 defaults `--host 0.0.0.0`, making the dashboard LAN-exposed with no authentication. Current `main.py` line 114 hardcodes `reload=True` in uvicorn.run, which is a dev-time feature that wastes resources in production and leaks file paths.\n\nThis is the single lowest-effort, highest-impact security fix. One line eliminates the entire LAN attack surface.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Edit `main.py` `cmd_dashboard` function:\n   ```python\n   def cmd_dashboard(args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:\n       import uvicorn\n\n       # Honor AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB if already set (e.g. from docker-compose),\n       # otherwise derive from --db argument. Fixes docker-compose path issue.\n       if not os.environ.get(\"AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB\"):\n           os.environ[\"AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB\"] = str(Path(args.db).resolve())\n\n       uvicorn.run(\n           \"dashboard.server:app\",\n           host=args.host,\n           port=int(args.port),\n           reload=args.reload,\n       )\n   ```\n\n2. Update the `dash` subparser definition (around line 188) to change the default and add --reload:\n   ```python\n   dash = sub.add_parser(\"dashboard\", help=\"Launch web dashboard\")\n   dash.add_argument(\"--db\", type=str, default=\"am4_data.db\")\n   dash.add_argument(\"--port\", type=int, default=8000)\n   dash.add_argument(\n       \"--host\",\n       type=str,\n       default=\"127.0.0.1\",\n       help=\"Bind address. Default 127.0.0.1 (localhost only). \"\n            \"Use 0.0.0.0 for LAN access - no auth, use only on trusted networks.\",\n   )\n   dash.add_argument(\n       \"--reload\",\n       action=\"store_true\",\n       help=\"Enable uvicorn auto-reload (dev only, wastes resources otherwise).\",\n   )\n   dash.set_defaults(func=cmd_dashboard)\n   ```\n\n3. Update the README:\n   - Under the Dashboard section, add a short note:\n     \"By default the dashboard binds to 127.0.0.1 only. To access from other devices on your LAN, run `python main.py dashboard --host 0.0.0.0` - **there is no authentication**, use only on trusted networks.\"\n   - Under Troubleshooting, add: \"Can't reach dashboard from another device: that's expected - see `--host` above.\"\n\n4. Update the `docker-compose.yml` command section (if the compose file needs to expose the dashboard across the Docker bridge, it must pass `--host 0.0.0.0`). Add a `command:` override:\n   ```yaml\n   services:\n     routemine:\n       ...\n       command: python main.py dashboard --host 0.0.0.0 --db /app/data/am4_data.db\n   ```\n   This fixes both the host binding (required for Docker bridge access) AND the db path issue (SEC/functional - `cmd_dashboard` previously overwrote `AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB`).\n\n5. Commit: `git add main.py README.md docker-compose.yml && git commit -m \"security: default --host 127.0.0.1, --reload opt-in, honor AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py dashboard --help` - confirm host default shows 127.0.0.1 and --reload is listed. Run `python main.py dashboard &` briefly, then `curl -s http://127.0.0.1:8000/ | head -c 50` - should return HTML. Run `curl -s --max-time 2 http://$(hostname -I | awk '{print $1}'):8000/ 2>&1` - should fail to connect (localhost-only). Kill the dashboard. Run `python main.py dashboard --host 0.0.0.0 &`, then the LAN curl should succeed. Kill again.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:07:00.348Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "6",
        "title": "Add schema unique constraints (route_aircraft, aircraft, airports)",
        "description": "Add UNIQUE constraints to route_aircraft, aircraft.shortname, and airports.iata to eliminate silent data duplication and nondeterministic lookups.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit items 1 and 2 - the highest-impact schema correctness fixes.\n\nProblems:\n1. `route_aircraft` has no unique constraint on (origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id). The only thing preventing duplicate rows is the `_delete_routes_for_origin` call in `refresh_single_hub_conn`. Any future insertion path that skips the delete silently double-counts profit totals.\n2. `aircraft.shortname` and `airports.iata` are not UNIQUE. `_aircraft_id` and `_airport_id` helpers in `commands/airline.py` use `LIMIT 1` without `ORDER BY` - lookups become nondeterministic if duplicates ever appear.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Edit `database/schema.py` SCHEMA_SQL. In the `route_aircraft` table definition, change the existing constraints block to add:\n   ```sql\n   CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS route_aircraft (\n       id                  INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n       ...existing columns...\n       extracted_at        TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,\n\n       FOREIGN KEY (origin_id)   REFERENCES airports(id),\n       FOREIGN KEY (dest_id)     REFERENCES airports(id),\n       FOREIGN KEY (aircraft_id) REFERENCES aircraft(id),\n       UNIQUE(origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id)\n   );\n   ```\n\n2. In the `aircraft` table definition, change `shortname TEXT NOT NULL,` to `shortname TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE,`.\n\n3. In the `airports` table, add after the CREATE TABLE block:\n   ```sql\n   CREATE UNIQUE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_airports_iata_unique\n       ON airports(iata) WHERE iata IS NOT NULL AND TRIM(iata) != '';\n   ```\n   A partial index is needed because some airports have NULL IATA codes.\n\n4. Update `extractors/routes.py` `_insert_batches` to use ON CONFLICT upsert so that the extractor is idempotent even without pre-deletion:\n   ```python\n   ROUTE_INSERT_SQL = \"\"\"\n   INSERT INTO route_aircraft (\n       origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id, distance_km,\n       ...all columns...\n       game_mode\n   ) VALUES (\n       :origin_id, :dest_id, :aircraft_id, :distance_km,\n       ...all placeholders...\n       :game_mode\n   )\n   ON CONFLICT(origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id) DO UPDATE SET\n       distance_km = excluded.distance_km,\n       config_y = excluded.config_y,\n       config_j = excluded.config_j,\n       config_f = excluded.config_f,\n       config_algorithm = excluded.config_algorithm,\n       ticket_y = excluded.ticket_y,\n       ticket_j = excluded.ticket_j,\n       ticket_f = excluded.ticket_f,\n       income = excluded.income,\n       fuel_cost = excluded.fuel_cost,\n       co2_cost = excluded.co2_cost,\n       repair_cost = excluded.repair_cost,\n       acheck_cost = excluded.acheck_cost,\n       profit_per_trip = excluded.profit_per_trip,\n       flight_time_hrs = excluded.flight_time_hrs,\n       trips_per_day = excluded.trips_per_day,\n       num_aircraft = excluded.num_aircraft,\n       profit_per_ac_day = excluded.profit_per_ac_day,\n       income_per_ac_day = excluded.income_per_ac_day,\n       contribution = excluded.contribution,\n       needs_stopover = excluded.needs_stopover,\n       stopover_iata = excluded.stopover_iata,\n       total_distance = excluded.total_distance,\n       ci = excluded.ci,\n       warnings = excluded.warnings,\n       is_valid = excluded.is_valid,\n       game_mode = excluded.game_mode,\n       extracted_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP\n   \"\"\"\n   ```\n\n5. Migration step - the existing databases in users' environments need the new constraints applied. Add a one-shot migration helper in `database/schema.py`:\n   ```python\n   def migrate_add_unique_constraints(conn: sqlite3.Connection) -> None:\n       \"\"\"Apply unique constraints to existing DBs created before the schema update.\n       Safe to run multiple times.\"\"\"\n       # Check if route_aircraft already has the unique constraint\n       row = conn.execute(\n           \"SELECT sql FROM sqlite_master WHERE type='table' AND name='route_aircraft'\"\n       ).fetchone()\n       if row and \"UNIQUE(origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id)\" in (row[0] or \"\"):\n           return  # already migrated\n\n       conn.execute(\"BEGIN\")\n       try:\n           # 1. Deduplicate any existing duplicates, keeping the newest\n           conn.execute(\"\"\"\n               DELETE FROM route_aircraft\n               WHERE id NOT IN (\n                   SELECT MAX(id) FROM route_aircraft\n                   GROUP BY origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id\n               )\n           \"\"\")\n           # 2. Rebuild route_aircraft with the new constraint (SQLite can't ALTER TABLE ADD CONSTRAINT)\n           conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n               CREATE TABLE route_aircraft__new AS SELECT * FROM route_aircraft;\n               DROP TABLE route_aircraft;\n           \"\"\")\n           # 3. Re-run create_schema which will now create with UNIQUE\n           create_schema(conn)\n           # 4. Copy data back\n           conn.execute(\"\"\"\n               INSERT INTO route_aircraft SELECT * FROM route_aircraft__new\n           \"\"\")\n           conn.execute(\"DROP TABLE route_aircraft__new\")\n           conn.commit()\n       except Exception:\n           conn.rollback()\n           raise\n   ```\n\n   Then in `main.py`, add a new subcommand `python main.py migrate --db am4_data.db` that calls this. Do NOT run migration automatically on every connection - it's a one-shot operation.\n\n6. Add test to verify duplicates raise IntegrityError:\n   ```python\n   # tests/test_schema.py\n   def test_route_aircraft_unique_constraint(tmp_path):\n       db = tmp_path / \"test.db\"\n       conn = get_connection(db)\n       create_schema(conn)\n       # insert minimal required rows...\n       conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO aircraft (id, shortname, name, type) VALUES (1, 'b738', 'B737-800', 'PAX')\")\n       conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO airports (id, iata) VALUES (1, 'KHI'), (2, 'DXB')\")\n       conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO route_aircraft (origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id) VALUES (1, 2, 1)\")\n       with pytest.raises(sqlite3.IntegrityError):\n           conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO route_aircraft (origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id) VALUES (1, 2, 1)\")\n   ```\n\n7. Commit: `git add database/schema.py extractors/routes.py main.py tests/ && git commit -m \"fix(schema): add unique constraints + upsert to route_aircraft\"`\n\nSuperpowers note: This is a high-stakes schema change - use the `test-driven-development` skill. Write the failing IntegrityError test FIRST, confirm it fails on the old schema, then apply the constraint, then confirm it passes.",
        "testStrategy": "Apply schema to a fresh DB and run the integrity test above. Run the migration on a copy of a real am4_data.db and confirm (a) it completes without error, (b) row counts before and after match for unique (origin, dest, ac) combinations, (c) a subsequent duplicate insert raises IntegrityError. Run `python main.py extract --hubs KHI --mode easy` twice in a row without the delete-then-insert pattern and confirm the second run does not create duplicates.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:17:41.986Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "7",
        "title": "Delete routes in FK-safe order and wrap replace_master_tables in try/finally",
        "description": "Fix the latent FK-disabled-forever bug in replace_master_tables and the dangling-reference window during full rebuilds.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "6"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - `replace_master_tables` disables foreign keys, then deletes from aircraft and airports, then re-enables FKs only at the end. If anything raises between OFF and the final ON, the connection is left with FKs permanently disabled. Additionally, deleting aircraft and airports while FKs are off leaves dangling references in route_aircraft, my_fleet, my_routes, my_hubs.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Edit `database/schema.py` `replace_master_tables`:\n   ```python\n   def replace_master_tables(conn: sqlite3.Connection) -> None:\n       \"\"\"Clear aircraft and airports master tables in FK-safe order.\n\n       We delete route_aircraft and route_demands first so that removing\n       aircraft/airports doesn't leave dangling references. The user's own\n       tables (my_fleet, my_routes, my_hubs) reference aircraft/airports by\n       ID - since am4 assigns IDs deterministically, a subsequent extract\n       will re-populate the same IDs. If that invariant ever breaks, we'd\n       rather get an IntegrityError than silently orphan user data.\n       \"\"\"\n       try:\n           conn.execute(\"PRAGMA foreign_keys = OFF\")\n           conn.execute(\"BEGIN\")\n           # Delete in dependency order: derived tables first\n           conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM route_aircraft\")\n           conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM route_demands\")\n           # Then master tables\n           conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM aircraft\")\n           conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM airports\")\n           # Reset autoincrement counters so IDs don't drift indefinitely\n           conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM sqlite_sequence WHERE name IN ('route_aircraft', 'aircraft', 'airports')\")\n           conn.commit()\n       except Exception:\n           conn.rollback()\n           raise\n       finally:\n           # ALWAYS re-enable FKs, even on error. Prevents connection poisoning.\n           conn.execute(\"PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON\")\n   ```\n\n   Note: `clear_route_tables` is now redundant with the first two DELETEs above but keep it for the single-hub refresh path.\n\n2. Also fix `clear_route_tables` to reset the sqlite_sequence for route_aircraft (addresses the low-priority note about ever-climbing AUTOINCREMENT values):\n   ```python\n   def clear_route_tables(conn: sqlite3.Connection) -> None:\n       conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM route_aircraft\")\n       conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM route_demands\")\n       conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM sqlite_sequence WHERE name = 'route_aircraft'\")\n       conn.commit()\n   ```\n\n3. Add a test that confirms FK enforcement is restored after an exception:\n   ```python\n   def test_replace_master_tables_restores_fk_on_error(tmp_path):\n       db = tmp_path / \"test.db\"\n       conn = get_connection(db)\n       create_schema(conn)\n       # Force an error by taking an exclusive lock from another conn\n       # ... or simpler: monkey-patch the first DELETE to raise\n       with patch.object(conn, 'execute', side_effect=sqlite3.OperationalError(\"boom\")):\n           with pytest.raises(sqlite3.OperationalError):\n               replace_master_tables(conn)\n       # Verify FKs are ON again\n       row = conn.execute(\"PRAGMA foreign_keys\").fetchone()\n       assert row[0] == 1\n   ```\n\n4. Commit: `git add database/schema.py tests/ && git commit -m \"fix(schema): FK-safe delete order and try/finally in replace_master_tables\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run the unit test above. Run a full extract cycle on a test DB, interrupt it partway (Ctrl-C during the route computation phase), reopen the DB, and confirm `PRAGMA foreign_keys;` returns 1. Run a second extract on the same DB and confirm it completes without IntegrityError.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:27:37.306Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "8",
        "title": "Parameterize STALE_AFTER_DAYS in SQL queries",
        "description": "Fix SEC-02 - eliminate f-string SQL interpolation of STALE_AFTER_DAYS in three locations.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "high",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-02. Three locations in `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py` interpolate STALE_AFTER_DAYS into SQL via f-string. Today `STALE_AFTER_DAYS` is the integer `7` so there's no exploit, but the pattern is a latent injection vector.\n\nSQLite's `datetime()` modifier strings cannot be parameterized directly. The fix is to compute the cutoff timestamp in Python and pass it as a bound parameter.\n\nLocations to fix:\n1. `api_hubs_summary` (around line 1887) - SELECT with SUM(CASE...) clauses comparing last_extracted_at\n2. `api_hubs_refresh_stale` (around line 2053) - SELECT filtering stale hubs\n3. Any other occurrence - grep for `days'\"` in api_routes.py to verify\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add a helper at the top of `api_routes.py` (after imports):\n   ```python\n   from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\n\n   def _stale_cutoff_iso(days: int = STALE_AFTER_DAYS) -> str:\n       \"\"\"Return an ISO-format timestamp for 'now minus N days' in UTC.\n\n       Used as a bound parameter to SQL - never interpolate days directly.\n       \"\"\"\n       cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=days)\n       return cutoff.strftime(\"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\")\n   ```\n\n2. Replace the f-string in `api_hubs_summary`:\n   ```python\n   cutoff = _stale_cutoff_iso()\n   row = fetch_one(\n       conn,\n       \"\"\"\n       SELECT COUNT(*) AS total,\n              SUM(CASE WHEN is_active = 1 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS active,\n              SUM(CASE\n                WHEN last_extract_status = 'ok' AND NOT (\n                  last_extracted_at IS NOT NULL\n                  AND TRIM(last_extracted_at) != ''\n                  AND datetime(last_extracted_at) IS NOT NULL\n                  AND datetime(last_extracted_at) < datetime(?)\n                ) THEN 1 ELSE 0\n              END) AS fresh_ok,\n              SUM(CASE\n                WHEN last_extract_status = 'ok'\n                 AND last_extracted_at IS NOT NULL\n                 AND TRIM(last_extracted_at) != ''\n                 AND datetime(last_extracted_at) IS NOT NULL\n                 AND datetime(last_extracted_at) < datetime(?)\n                THEN 1 ELSE 0\n              END) AS stale_n,\n              SUM(CASE\n                WHEN last_extract_status = 'error' THEN 1\n                WHEN last_extract_status = 'running' THEN 1\n                WHEN last_extract_status IS NULL\n                  OR TRIM(COALESCE(last_extract_status, '')) = '' THEN 1\n                WHEN last_extract_status NOT IN ('ok', 'error', 'running') THEN 1\n                ELSE 0\n              END) AS other_n\n       FROM my_hubs\n       \"\"\",\n       [cutoff, cutoff],\n   )\n   ```\n\n3. Replace the f-string in `api_hubs_refresh_stale`:\n   ```python\n   cutoff = _stale_cutoff_iso()\n   stale = fetch_all(\n       conn,\n       \"\"\"\n       SELECT id, iata FROM v_my_hubs\n       WHERE last_extract_status = 'ok'\n         AND last_extracted_at IS NOT NULL\n         AND TRIM(last_extracted_at) != ''\n         AND datetime(last_extracted_at) IS NOT NULL\n         AND datetime(last_extracted_at) < datetime(?)\n       ORDER BY iata COLLATE NOCASE\n       \"\"\",\n       [cutoff],\n   )\n   ```\n\n4. Update the user-visible message in `api_hubs_refresh_stale` to still read naturally - it already uses `d = STALE_AFTER_DAYS` for the flash string, leave that as-is.\n\n5. Commit: `git add dashboard/routes/api_routes.py && git commit -m \"security(SEC-02): parameterize STALE_AFTER_DAYS in SQL queries\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Grep the file after the change: `grep -n \"datetime('now', '-\" dashboard/routes/api_routes.py` - should return nothing. `grep -n 'days}\"' dashboard/routes/api_routes.py` - should return nothing. Launch the dashboard, navigate to Hub Manager, verify the summary cards load. Verify the 'Refresh Stale' action still identifies and refreshes hubs older than 7 days.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:07:00.364Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "9",
        "title": "Persist UserConfig per extraction in an extract_metadata table",
        "description": "Fix the systemic config drift issue: CLI extract uses one config, dashboard refresh uses bare defaults, and recommend doesn't know the config at all. Persist the config used for each extraction.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "6"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit cross-cutting issue - the single biggest analytical-correctness gap. Currently `_dashboard_extract_config()` returns `UserConfig()` with bare defaults, so a dashboard hub refresh produces inconsistent economics vs. a CLI extract done with `--reputation 95`.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add `extract_metadata` table to `database/schema.py` SCHEMA_SQL:\n   ```sql\n   CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS extract_metadata (\n       key         TEXT PRIMARY KEY,\n       value       TEXT,\n       updated_at  TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP\n   );\n   ```\n\n2. Add helper functions in `database/schema.py`:\n   ```python\n   def save_extract_config(conn: sqlite3.Connection, cfg) -> None:\n       \"\"\"Persist the UserConfig used for an extraction. Called by run_bulk_extraction.\"\"\"\n       from dataclasses import asdict\n       import json\n       payload = asdict(cfg)\n       # Enum serialization\n       payload[\"game_mode\"] = cfg.game_mode.value\n       for k, v in payload.items():\n           conn.execute(\n               \"\"\"\n               INSERT INTO extract_metadata (key, value, updated_at)\n               VALUES (?, ?, datetime('now'))\n               ON CONFLICT(key) DO UPDATE SET\n                   value = excluded.value,\n                   updated_at = datetime('now')\n               \"\"\",\n               (k, json.dumps(v)),\n           )\n       conn.commit()\n\n   def load_extract_config(conn: sqlite3.Connection):\n       \"\"\"Load the UserConfig previously saved. Returns None if no data.\"\"\"\n       from config import UserConfig, GameMode\n       import json\n       rows = conn.execute(\"SELECT key, value FROM extract_metadata\").fetchall()\n       if not rows:\n           return None\n       data = {r[0]: json.loads(r[1]) for r in rows}\n       if \"game_mode\" in data:\n           data[\"game_mode\"] = GameMode(data[\"game_mode\"])\n       # Filter to known fields to tolerate schema evolution\n       from dataclasses import fields\n       known = {f.name for f in fields(UserConfig)}\n       data = {k: v for k, v in data.items() if k in known}\n       return UserConfig(**data)\n   ```\n\n3. Call `save_extract_config(conn, cfg)` at the end of `run_bulk_extraction` in `extractors/routes.py`:\n   ```python\n   _insert_batches(conn, all_routes, demand_map)\n   save_extract_config(conn, cfg)\n   print(f\"    → {len(all_routes)} route rows, {len(demand_map)} origin-destination demand rows\")\n   conn.close()\n   ```\n\n4. Update `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py` `_dashboard_extract_config`:\n   ```python\n   def _dashboard_extract_config() -> UserConfig:\n       \"\"\"Load the UserConfig that was used for the last full extraction.\n       Falls back to defaults only if no extraction has ever run.\"\"\"\n       try:\n           conn = get_db()\n           try:\n               from database.schema import load_extract_config\n               cfg = load_extract_config(conn)\n               return cfg if cfg is not None else UserConfig()\n           finally:\n               conn.close()\n       except (FileNotFoundError, sqlite3.OperationalError):\n           return UserConfig()\n   ```\n\n5. Also call `save_extract_config` at the end of `refresh_single_hub_conn` so that hub refreshes keep the metadata fresh.\n\n6. Add a CLI subcommand to display current metadata:\n   ```\n   python main.py extract-info --db am4_data.db\n   ```\n   that loads and prints the saved UserConfig.\n\n7. Commit: `git add database/schema.py extractors/routes.py dashboard/routes/api_routes.py main.py && git commit -m \"feat: persist UserConfig per extraction and use in dashboard refresh\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py extract --hubs KHI --reputation 95 --ci 180` on a test DB, then query: `sqlite3 test.db \"SELECT * FROM extract_metadata\"` - should show reputation=95.0 and cost_index=180. Trigger a hub refresh from the dashboard and confirm it uses the same reputation (add a debug print temporarily or check the saved rows match). Run `python main.py extract-info --db test.db` and verify output matches what was passed in.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:42:57.810Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "10",
        "title": "Derive total_planes_owned from my_fleet",
        "description": "Fix the hardcoded 50-plane default - AM4's purchase discount scales with fleet size, so every extraction and recommendation is priced for a 50-plane airline regardless of reality.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "9"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - `config.py` hardcodes `total_planes_owned = 50`. This value feeds into am4's User object (`user.accumulated_count = int(cfg.total_planes_owned)`) and drives the bulk-purchase discount. A 172-plane airline gets a meaningfully lower price than a 50-plane airline, so both route economics and the Buy Next breakeven math are skewed.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add a helper in `config.py` or `database/schema.py`:\n   ```python\n   def derived_total_planes(conn: sqlite3.Connection) -> int | None:\n       \"\"\"Return SUM(quantity) from my_fleet, or None if the table is empty.\"\"\"\n       try:\n           row = conn.execute(\n               \"SELECT COALESCE(SUM(quantity), 0) FROM my_fleet\"\n           ).fetchone()\n           n = int(row[0] or 0) if row else 0\n           return n if n > 0 else None\n       except sqlite3.OperationalError:\n           return None\n   ```\n\n2. Update `main.py` `_config_from_extract_args` to apply the derived value when no CLI override is given:\n   ```python\n   def _config_from_extract_args(args: argparse.Namespace) -> UserConfig:\n       cfg = UserConfig(\n           game_mode=GameMode.EASY if args.mode == \"easy\" else GameMode.REALISM,\n           cost_index=int(args.ci),\n           reputation=float(args.reputation),\n           max_workers=int(args.workers),\n       )\n       if args.planes_owned is not None:\n           cfg.total_planes_owned = int(args.planes_owned)\n       else:\n           # Derive from my_fleet if available\n           from database.schema import get_connection, derived_total_planes\n           try:\n               conn = get_connection(args.db)\n               derived = derived_total_planes(conn)\n               conn.close()\n               if derived is not None:\n                   cfg.total_planes_owned = derived\n                   print(f\"Using total_planes_owned={derived} derived from my_fleet.\")\n           except Exception:\n               pass\n       ... rest of existing logic ...\n   ```\n\n3. Add the new CLI flag:\n   ```python\n   ex.add_argument(\n       \"--planes-owned\",\n       type=int,\n       default=None,\n       help=\"Override total_planes_owned. Default: derived from my_fleet SUM(quantity), or 50.\",\n   )\n   ```\n\n4. Update `_dashboard_extract_config` in `api_routes.py` to also apply the derivation (after loading from extract_metadata from task 9):\n   ```python\n   def _dashboard_extract_config() -> UserConfig:\n       cfg = ... # existing load logic from task 9\n       try:\n           conn = get_db()\n           try:\n               from database.schema import derived_total_planes\n               derived = derived_total_planes(conn)\n               if derived is not None:\n                   cfg.total_planes_owned = derived\n           finally:\n               conn.close()\n       except Exception:\n           pass\n       return cfg\n   ```\n\n5. Update `fleet_recommend.py` docstring to mention that recommendations assume the current my_fleet size drives discount pricing.\n\n6. Commit: `git add main.py config.py database/schema.py dashboard/routes/api_routes.py commands/fleet_recommend.py && git commit -m \"feat: derive total_planes_owned from my_fleet\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Import a fleet CSV: `python main.py fleet import --file test_fleet.csv` where the CSV totals 172 planes. Run `python main.py extract --hubs KHI` and observe the printed \"Using total_planes_owned=172...\" message. Query `sqlite3 test.db \"SELECT value FROM extract_metadata WHERE key='total_planes_owned'\"` - should return 172. Override with `python main.py extract --hubs KHI --planes-owned 50` and confirm the override wins.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T01:42:57.822Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "11",
        "title": "Per-hub commits in run_bulk_extraction",
        "description": "Fix the giant-transaction bug where 3.8M rows are accumulated in memory before a single commit. Interruption loses everything.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "6"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit item 5 - contradicts the userMemory note claiming per-hub commits already fix a ThreadPoolExecutor hang. Either the fix regressed or the note was about a different bug.\n\nCurrent code in `run_bulk_extraction` accumulates `all_routes: list[dict] = []` and `demand_map: dict = {}` across every worker, then writes with a single `_insert_batches` call at the end. For a 6-hub × 172-aircraft extraction that's ~3.8M rows held in Python memory, and any interruption loses hours of computation.\n\nNote: This task depends on the upsert changes from task 6 - per-hub commits are safe because the UNIQUE constraint + ON CONFLICT means reruns don't duplicate.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Rewrite `run_bulk_extraction` in `extractors/routes.py` to commit per hub. Use a thread-safe queue pattern:\n   ```python\n   def run_bulk_extraction(db_path: str, cfg: UserConfig) -> None:\n       from tqdm import tqdm\n       import queue\n       import threading\n\n       conn = get_connection(db_path)\n       create_schema(conn)\n       clear_route_tables(conn)\n       replace_master_tables(conn)\n\n       print(\"[1/3] Extracting aircraft...\")\n       aircraft_rows = extract_all_aircraft(conn)\n       print(f\"    -> {len(aircraft_rows)} aircraft\")\n\n       print(\"[2/3] Extracting airports...\")\n       airport_rows = extract_all_airports(conn, cfg)\n       print(f\"    -> {len(airport_rows)} airports\")\n\n       if cfg.hubs:\n           hubs = [h.strip().upper() for h in cfg.hubs if h.strip()]\n       else:\n           hubs = [a[\"iata\"] for a in airport_rows if a.get(\"iata\")]\n\n       if cfg.hub_filter:\n           allow = {h.strip().upper() for h in cfg.hub_filter if h.strip()}\n           hubs = [h for h in hubs if h in allow]\n\n       game_mode_label = cfg.game_mode.value\n       print(\n           f\"[3/3] Computing routes for {len(hubs)} hubs x {len(aircraft_rows)} \"\n           f\"aircraft (workers={cfg.max_workers})...\"\n       )\n\n       total_routes = 0\n       total_demands = 0\n       workers = max(1, int(cfg.max_workers))\n\n       def _build_user_and_options():\n           \"\"\"Per-thread construction to avoid shared-object races (task 12).\"\"\"\n           return build_am4_user(cfg), _aircraft_route_options(cfg)\n\n       if workers == 1:\n           user, options = _build_user_and_options()\n           for hub in tqdm(hubs):\n               rr, dd = extract_routes_for_hub(\n                   hub, aircraft_rows, cfg, user, options, game_mode_label\n               )\n               _insert_batches(conn, rr, _demands_to_map(dd))\n               total_routes += len(rr)\n               total_demands += len(dd)\n       else:\n           # Worker threads produce rows; a single writer thread commits per hub.\n           from concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor, as_completed\n           with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=workers) as ex:\n               futs = {}\n               for hub in hubs:\n                   def _task(h=hub):\n                       user, options = _build_user_and_options()\n                       return extract_routes_for_hub(\n                           h, aircraft_rows, cfg, user, options, game_mode_label\n                       )\n                   futs[ex.submit(_task)] = hub\n               for fut in tqdm(as_completed(futs), total=len(futs), desc=\"Hubs\"):\n                   hub = futs[fut]\n                   try:\n                       rr, dd = fut.result()\n                   except Exception as exc:\n                       print(f\"    ! {hub}: {exc}\")\n                       continue\n                   _insert_batches(conn, rr, _demands_to_map(dd))\n                   total_routes += len(rr)\n                   total_demands += len(dd)\n\n       save_extract_config(conn, cfg)  # from task 9\n       print(f\"    -> {total_routes} route rows, {total_demands} demand rows\")\n       conn.close()\n   ```\n\n2. This closes four audit items at once:\n   - Per-hub commits (this task)\n   - Shared user/options across threads (task 12)\n   - Silent exception swallowing on per-hub failures (partial fix - adds hub name to error)\n   - Memory pressure from accumulating 3.8M rows\n\n3. Commit: `git add extractors/routes.py && git commit -m \"fix(extraction): per-hub commits, per-thread user/options, memory-safe\"`\n\nSuperpowers: Use `systematic-debugging` skill if the ThreadPoolExecutor ever hangs again during testing - don't guess at root cause, instrument it.",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py extract --hubs KHI,DXB,LHR,JFK,HKG,MJD --workers 4 --mode easy` and confirm it completes without hanging. Interrupt a similar run with Ctrl-C midway through hub 3 of 6 and confirm: (a) process terminates promptly, (b) hubs 1-2 are fully present in route_aircraft, (c) hub 3 may be partial or absent, (d) a subsequent rerun (or refresh-hubs) successfully completes the missing hubs. Compare total row counts before and after to pre-change extraction: should be identical.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T02:15:00.687Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "12",
        "title": "Log silent except Exception catches in extractors",
        "description": "Replace the three silent `except Exception: continue` blocks in extract_routes_for_hub and the ones in aircraft/airports extractors with logged warnings.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - extract_routes_for_hub (lines 81, 98, 107 in routes.py), plus similar patterns in extractors/aircraft.py and extractors/airports.py. Currently if am4 fails on one aircraft or one hub's geometry, the extraction silently produces partial results with no indication.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add a logger at the top of `extractors/routes.py`:\n   ```python\n   import logging\n   log = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n   ```\n\n2. Replace each silent catch in `extract_routes_for_hub`:\n   ```python\n   try:\n       hub_res = Airport.search(hub_iata.strip())\n       hub = hub_res.ap\n   except Exception as exc:\n       log.warning(\"hub lookup failed for %s: %s\", hub_iata, exc)\n       return route_rows, demand_rows\n\n   ...\n\n   try:\n       ac = Aircraft.search(sn).ac\n   except Exception as exc:\n       log.warning(\"aircraft lookup failed for %s at hub %s: %s\", sn, hub_iata, exc)\n       continue\n\n   ...\n\n   try:\n       search = RoutesSearch(ap0=[hub], ac=ac, options=options, user=user)\n       destinations = search.get()\n   except Exception as exc:\n       log.warning(\n           \"RoutesSearch failed for hub=%s aircraft=%s: %s\",\n           hub_iata, sn, exc\n       )\n       continue\n   ```\n\n3. Same treatment in `extractors/aircraft.py` and `extractors/airports.py`:\n   ```python\n   except Exception as exc:\n       log.warning(\"skipped aircraft id=%d: %s\", ac_id, exc)\n       continue\n   ```\n   And add a counter, printed at end:\n   ```python\n   n_skipped = 0\n   ...\n   except Exception as exc:\n       n_skipped += 1\n       log.warning(\"skipped aircraft id=%d: %s\", ac_id, exc)\n       continue\n   ...\n   if n_skipped:\n       print(f\"    ! skipped {n_skipped} aircraft IDs due to am4 errors\")\n   ```\n\n4. Configure logging in `main.py` so warnings show by default during extraction:\n   ```python\n   def cmd_extract(args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:\n       import logging\n       logging.basicConfig(\n           level=logging.INFO,\n           format=\"%(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(name)s: %(message)s\",\n       )\n       from am4.utils.db import init\n       ...\n   ```\n\n5. Commit: `git add extractors/ main.py && git commit -m \"observability: log silent exception catches in extractors\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py extract --hubs ZZZ --mode easy` (bogus hub) - should log a warning identifying ZZZ, not silently return 0 routes. Run with a real hub and confirm no warnings appear for successful operations. Run with `--aircraft someinvalidname,b738` and confirm the invalid name is logged but b738 extraction proceeds.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T02:15:00.698Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "13",
        "title": "Warn or block --workers on --refresh-hubs",
        "description": "Fix the user-facing surprise where --workers is silently ignored in refresh mode.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - `refresh_hubs` in `extractors/routes.py` is a plain sequential for loop over `hub_iatas`. The CLI still accepts `--workers 4` on `extract --refresh-hubs` but silently ignores it.\n\nOption A (chosen): Print a warning if workers > 1 and refresh-hubs is set.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Edit `main.py` `cmd_extract` in the refresh-hubs branch:\n   ```python\n   if args.refresh_hubs:\n       if args.all_hubs:\n           print(\"Error: --refresh-hubs cannot be used with --all-hubs\", file=sys.stderr)\n           sys.exit(2)\n       if not args.hubs or not str(args.hubs).strip():\n           print(\"Error: --refresh-hubs requires --hubs IATA1,IATA2\", file=sys.stderr)\n           sys.exit(2)\n       if int(args.workers) > 1:\n           print(\n               f\"Note: --workers {args.workers} is ignored in --refresh-hubs mode \"\n               \"(hubs are refreshed sequentially to avoid SQLite write contention).\",\n               file=sys.stderr,\n           )\n       from extractors.routes import refresh_hubs\n       hub_list = [x.strip() for x in args.hubs.split(\",\") if x.strip()]\n       refresh_hubs(args.db, cfg, hub_list)\n       print(f\"Refreshed routes for {len(hub_list)} hub(s).\")\n       return\n   ```\n\n2. Commit: `git add main.py && git commit -m \"ux: warn when --workers is ignored in --refresh-hubs mode\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py extract --refresh-hubs --hubs KHI --workers 4 2>&1 | grep -i ignored` - should match. Run without --workers or with --workers 1 and confirm no warning.",
        "subtasks": [],
        "updatedAt": "2026-04-06T02:15:00.708Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "14",
        "title": "Fix CSV import aircraft shortname mappings in convert_csv.py",
        "description": "Port the corrected aircraft shortname mappings from routemine learnings. Several entries in the current convert_csv.py are wrong or marked '# verify' and committed without validation.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: From the first-pass audit. Several entries in `AIRCRAFT_MAP` in `convert_csv.py` are incorrect per the corrections documented in routemine userMemories.\n\nKnown corrections (from the prior routemine project):\n- `A320-200` should map to `a322` (not `a320`)\n- `A220-100` should map to `a221` (not `a220-100`)\n- `ERJ 170-200` should map to `erj172` (not `e175`)\n- `ATR 42-320` should map to `atr4232` (not `at43`)\n- `B737 MAX 9` should map to `b73max9` (not `b39m`)\n- `Bombardier Challenger 605-VIP` should map to `ch605` (not `cl60`)\n- `Cessna Citation X-VIP` should map to `ccx` (not `c750`)\n- `DC-9-10` should map to `dc910` (not `dc91`)\n\nPlus `A310-300F`, `A350F`, `B737-700C` are all marked `# verify` and were never checked.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Verify each mapping against a live am4 session. Create a small script `scripts/verify_aircraft_map.py`:\n   ```python\n   #!/usr/bin/env python3\n   \"\"\"Verify every entry in AIRCRAFT_MAP resolves to a valid am4 shortname.\"\"\"\n   from am4.utils.db import init\n   init()\n   from am4.utils.aircraft import Aircraft\n   from convert_csv import AIRCRAFT_MAP\n\n   failed = []\n   for csv_name, shortname in AIRCRAFT_MAP.items():\n       try:\n           result = Aircraft.search(shortname)\n           if not result.ac.valid:\n               failed.append((csv_name, shortname, \"not valid\"))\n           else:\n               print(f\"OK  {csv_name:35s} -> {shortname:10s} ({result.ac.name})\")\n       except Exception as exc:\n           failed.append((csv_name, shortname, str(exc)))\n\n   if failed:\n       print(\"\\nFAILED:\")\n       for csv_name, shortname, err in failed:\n           print(f\"  {csv_name:35s} -> {shortname:10s}: {err}\")\n       raise SystemExit(1)\n   print(f\"\\n{len(AIRCRAFT_MAP)} mappings verified.\")\n   ```\n\n2. Run the verification script. For each failure, query am4 to find the correct shortname:\n   ```python\n   # Interactive debug:\n   from am4.utils.aircraft import Aircraft\n   # Try candidates\n   for sn in ['a320', 'a322', 'a320-200']:\n       try:\n           r = Aircraft.search(sn)\n           if r.ac.valid:\n               print(sn, '->', r.ac.name)\n       except Exception:\n           pass\n   ```\n\n3. Apply the corrected mappings to `AIRCRAFT_MAP` in `convert_csv.py`. Remove all `# verify` comments once verified.\n\n4. Re-run the verification script until it exits 0.\n\n5. Add `scripts/verify_aircraft_map.py` as a permanent part of the repo - it's useful when am4 updates.\n\n6. Commit: `git add convert_csv.py scripts/verify_aircraft_map.py && git commit -m \"fix(convert_csv): verify and correct aircraft shortname mappings\"`\n\nSuperpowers: Use `verification-before-completion` - run the verification script to prove every mapping actually resolves, don't trust the diff.",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python scripts/verify_aircraft_map.py` - exit code must be 0 and every line must print OK. Pick a real AM4 route CSV export, run `python convert_csv.py sample.csv`, and confirm `mapping_report.txt` shows zero UNMAPPED entries. Import the resulting fleet.csv and my_routes.csv via `python main.py fleet import` and `python main.py routes import` - both should complete without aircraft lookup errors.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "15",
        "title": "Atomic UPDATE for fleet buy/sell endpoints",
        "description": "Fix SEC-14 TOCTOU race. Current buy/sell endpoints read quantity, compute new value, then write - concurrent requests can lose writes.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-14. Current `api_fleet_buy` and `api_fleet_sell` in `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py` do read-then-write across separate implicit transactions. Two concurrent `buy 5` requests on a fleet with qty=10 can both write qty=15 instead of qty=20.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Rewrite `api_fleet_buy`:\n   ```python\n   @router.post(\"/fleet/{fleet_id}/buy\", response_class=HTMLResponse)\n   def api_fleet_buy(request: Request, fleet_id: int, add_count: int = Form(1)):\n       flash: str | None = None\n       flash_err: str | None = None\n       add = max(1, min(999, int(add_count) if add_count else 1))\n       try:\n           conn = get_db()\n           try:\n               # Atomic: UPDATE reads and writes in a single statement.\n               # The CASE expression caps at 999 to honor the CHECK constraint.\n               cur = conn.execute(\n                   \"\"\"\n                   UPDATE my_fleet\n                   SET quantity = MIN(999, quantity + ?),\n                       updated_at = datetime('now')\n                   WHERE id = ?\n                   \"\"\",\n                   (add, int(fleet_id)),\n               )\n               if cur.rowcount == 0:\n                   flash_err = \"Fleet row not found.\"\n               else:\n                   conn.commit()\n                   # Read back the new value for display\n                   row = fetch_one(\n                       conn,\n                       \"SELECT quantity FROM my_fleet WHERE id = ?\",\n                       (int(fleet_id),),\n                   )\n                   new_q = int(row[\"quantity\"]) if row else 0\n                   flash = f\"Bought (now {new_q} owned).\"\n           finally:\n               conn.close()\n       except FileNotFoundError:\n           flash_err = \"Database not found.\"\n       except sqlite3.OperationalError as exc:\n           flash_err = str(exc)\n\n       # Re-fetch inventory for HTMX refresh\n       try:\n           conn = get_db()\n           try:\n               fleets = _my_fleet_rows(conn)\n           finally:\n               conn.close()\n       except FileNotFoundError:\n           fleets = []\n       ctx: dict = {\"fleets\": fleets}\n       if flash_err:\n           ctx[\"flash_err\"] = flash_err\n       elif flash:\n           ctx[\"flash\"] = flash\n       return templates.TemplateResponse(request, \"partials/fleet_inventory.html\", ctx)\n   ```\n\n2. Rewrite `api_fleet_sell` - this is more complex because it must check the `free` (unassigned) count and may need to DELETE on sell-to-zero:\n   ```python\n   @router.post(\"/fleet/{fleet_id}/sell\", response_class=HTMLResponse)\n   def api_fleet_sell(request: Request, fleet_id: int, sell_count: int = Form(1)):\n       flash: str | None = None\n       flash_err: str | None = None\n       want = max(1, int(sell_count) if sell_count else 1)\n       try:\n           conn = get_db()\n           try:\n               # BEGIN IMMEDIATE gives us a write lock from the start,\n               # so the free-check and the UPDATE are atomic relative to other writers.\n               conn.execute(\"BEGIN IMMEDIATE\")\n               try:\n                   row = fetch_one(\n                       conn,\n                       \"\"\"\n                       SELECT mf.id, mf.quantity, mf.aircraft_id,\n                              COALESCE((\n                                  SELECT SUM(num_assigned) FROM my_routes\n                                  WHERE aircraft_id = mf.aircraft_id\n                              ), 0) AS assigned\n                       FROM my_fleet mf\n                       WHERE mf.id = ?\n                       \"\"\",\n                       (int(fleet_id),),\n                   )\n                   if not row:\n                       flash_err = \"Fleet row not found.\"\n                   else:\n                       qty = int(row[\"quantity\"] or 0)\n                       assigned = int(row[\"assigned\"] or 0)\n                       free = max(0, qty - assigned)\n                       if free <= 0:\n                           flash_err = \"No unassigned aircraft to sell (reduce My Routes assignments first).\"\n                       elif want > free:\n                           flash_err = f\"Only {free} unassigned; cannot sell {want}.\"\n                       else:\n                           new_q = qty - want\n                           if new_q <= 0:\n                               conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM my_fleet WHERE id = ?\", (int(fleet_id),))\n                               flash = f\"Sold all {qty}; removed type from fleet.\"\n                           else:\n                               conn.execute(\n                                   \"UPDATE my_fleet SET quantity = ?, updated_at = datetime('now') WHERE id = ?\",\n                                   (new_q, int(fleet_id)),\n                               )\n                               flash = f\"Sold {want} (now {new_q} owned).\"\n                   conn.commit()\n               except Exception:\n                   conn.rollback()\n                   raise\n           finally:\n               conn.close()\n       except FileNotFoundError:\n           flash_err = \"Database not found.\"\n       except sqlite3.OperationalError as exc:\n           flash_err = str(exc)\n\n       # inventory re-fetch same as buy\n       try:\n           conn = get_db()\n           try:\n               fleets = _my_fleet_rows(conn)\n           finally:\n               conn.close()\n       except FileNotFoundError:\n           fleets = []\n       ctx: dict = {\"fleets\": fleets}\n       if flash_err:\n           ctx[\"flash_err\"] = flash_err\n       elif flash:\n           ctx[\"flash\"] = flash\n       return templates.TemplateResponse(request, \"partials/fleet_inventory.html\", ctx)\n   ```\n\n3. Add a concurrency test:\n   ```python\n   # tests/test_fleet_concurrency.py\n   import threading\n   from fastapi.testclient import TestClient\n   from dashboard.server import app\n\n   def test_concurrent_buys_all_applied(tmp_fleet_db):\n       client = TestClient(app)\n       # Seed a fleet row with quantity=10\n       ...\n       def do_buy():\n           client.post(\"/api/fleet/1/buy\", data={\"add_count\": 5})\n       threads = [threading.Thread(target=do_buy) for _ in range(4)]\n       for t in threads: t.start()\n       for t in threads: t.join()\n       # All 4 buys must be applied: 10 + 4*5 = 30 (or capped at 999)\n       final = client.get(\"/api/fleet/json\").json()\n       assert final[0][\"quantity\"] == 30\n   ```\n\n4. Commit: `git add dashboard/routes/api_routes.py tests/ && git commit -m \"security(SEC-14): atomic buy/sell to eliminate TOCTOU race\"`\n\nSuperpowers: Use `test-driven-development` - write the concurrency test first, watch it fail on the old read-then-write code, then apply the fix.",
        "testStrategy": "Run the concurrency test. Manually: open two browser tabs on /my-fleet, click Buy +5 on the same row rapidly in both tabs - final quantity must reflect both clicks. Try selling more than free count via curl - should return the expected error. Try selling exactly the free count - should delete the row if sell brings quantity to 0.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "16",
        "title": "Concurrency lock on hub refresh endpoints (DoS mitigation)",
        "description": "Fix SEC-10 - hub refresh triggers unbounded CPU and blocks all other requests. Prevent concurrent refreshes.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-10. `POST /api/hubs/refresh` and `POST /api/hubs/refresh-stale` trigger full am4 RoutesSearch runs that block the uvicorn worker for minutes. With no auth (SEC-01, partially addressed by task 5) and no concurrency limiting, an attacker or accidental double-click can pin the CPU indefinitely.\n\nApproach: Use a process-level threading.Lock that gates all extraction. Concurrent requests return an immediate \"refresh already in progress\" error. This is simpler than BackgroundTasks and sufficient for a single-user tool.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add the lock and helper near the top of `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py`:\n   ```python\n   import threading\n\n   _EXTRACTION_LOCK = threading.Lock()\n\n   def _try_acquire_extraction_lock() -> bool:\n       \"\"\"Return True if lock was acquired (non-blocking). False if busy.\"\"\"\n       return _EXTRACTION_LOCK.acquire(blocking=False)\n\n   def _release_extraction_lock() -> None:\n       try:\n           _EXTRACTION_LOCK.release()\n       except RuntimeError:\n           pass  # not held\n   ```\n\n2. Wrap `api_hubs_refresh`:\n   ```python\n   @router.post(\"/hubs/refresh\", response_class=HTMLResponse)\n   def api_hubs_refresh(request: Request, hub_id: int = Form(...)):\n       if not _try_acquire_extraction_lock():\n           return _hub_inventory_response(\n               request,\n               flash_err=\"Another extraction is already in progress. Wait for it to finish.\",\n           )\n       try:\n           ... existing body ...\n       finally:\n           _release_extraction_lock()\n   ```\n\n3. Same treatment for `api_hubs_refresh_stale`.\n\n4. Optional hardening: add a `LAST_REFRESH_START` timestamp so the dashboard can show \"refresh in progress, started X seconds ago\" rather than a bare error.\n\n5. Also consider gating `api_hubs_add` since it calls `upsert_airport_from_am4` which does network/DB lookups in am4 - lighter weight than full extraction but still worth protecting.\n\n6. Commit: `git add dashboard/routes/api_routes.py && git commit -m \"security(SEC-10): concurrency lock on hub refresh endpoints\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Start a hub refresh in one terminal: `curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/hubs/refresh -d 'hub_id=1'`. Immediately in a second terminal, run the same curl. The second call should return the \"already in progress\" flash error. Confirm the first call completes normally. Launch `ab -n 100 -c 10 http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/hubs/refresh` and confirm the dashboard remains responsive to other requests during the refresh.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "17",
        "title": "HTML-escape airport names in heatmap Leaflet popup",
        "description": "Fix SEC-04 - airport name and IATA are interpolated into a JavaScript template literal that goes into innerHTML via Leaflet bindPopup.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-04. In `api_heatmap_panel` (around line 719-767 of api_routes.py), markers are serialized as JSON and then a JS popup template reads `m.iata`, `m.name`, `m.aircraft` and constructs HTML via template literal string concatenation, which Leaflet passes to `bindPopup()` - which sets it as HTML.\n\nThe JSON encoding step is already safe (json.dumps escapes `<`, `>`, `&`), but the popup template uses the raw string values. If an airport name ever contained HTML, it would execute.\n\nFix approach: Sanitize values before embedding in the JSON payload OR use DOM text APIs on the client side. The cleaner fix is client-side.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Change the inline popup JS to use `textContent` assignment rather than string concatenation into a template:\n   ```javascript\n   markers.forEach(m => {\n     const c = color(m.t);\n     const mk = L.circleMarker([m.lat, m.lng], {\n       radius: 8,\n       fillColor: c,\n       color: '#1f2937',\n       weight: 1,\n       fillOpacity: 0.85,\n     }).addTo(map);\n\n     // Build popup via DOM APIs, not HTML string concat - prevents XSS.\n     const popupEl = document.createElement('div');\n     const title = document.createElement('strong');\n     title.textContent = m.iata;\n     popupEl.appendChild(title);\n     if (m.name) {\n       popupEl.appendChild(document.createTextNode(' (' + m.name + ')'));\n     }\n     popupEl.appendChild(document.createElement('br'));\n     popupEl.appendChild(document.createTextNode('Profit/day: $' + Math.round(m.profit).toLocaleString()));\n     popupEl.appendChild(document.createElement('br'));\n     const small = document.createElement('span');\n     small.className = 'am4-text-muted text-xs';\n     small.textContent = (m.aircraft || '').slice(0, 120);\n     popupEl.appendChild(small);\n     mk.bindPopup(popupEl);\n\n     bounds.push([m.lat, m.lng]);\n   });\n   ```\n\n   `textContent` is the key - it treats its input as a plain string and doesn't parse HTML. Any `<script>` or `onerror=` in an airport name becomes inert text.\n\n2. Commit: `git add dashboard/routes/api_routes.py && git commit -m \"security(SEC-04): use textContent for heatmap popup to prevent XSS\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Temporarily insert a test airport with name `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>` into the DB via SQL, load the heatmap page for its hub, click the marker - the popup should display the literal string, not execute the script. Remove the test airport. Run the existing heatmap page against real data and confirm popups still display correctly.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "18",
        "title": "CSRF protection on POST endpoints via token middleware",
        "description": "Fix SEC-06 - no CSRF protection on any POST endpoint. Add a bearer-token auth middleware that doubles as CSRF protection.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "5"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-01 and SEC-06 (related). With the default host now 127.0.0.1 (task 5), the LAN attack surface is eliminated, but CSRF from the user's own browser to localhost is still possible. The simplest fix that addresses both unauth mutations and CSRF is a bearer token the client sends as an HTTP header - browsers can't forge arbitrary headers on cross-origin form submissions.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add a helper in `dashboard/server.py` (or a new `dashboard/auth.py`):\n   ```python\n   import os\n   import secrets\n   from fastapi import Request, HTTPException\n\n   # Read token from env or generate a per-process random one.\n   # If user sets AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN, it's shared across restarts.\n   # Otherwise we generate one at startup and print it.\n   _TOKEN = os.environ.get(\"AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN\")\n   if not _TOKEN:\n       _TOKEN = secrets.token_urlsafe(24)\n       print(f\"AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN not set. Generated session token: {_TOKEN}\")\n       print(\"Set AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN in your env to persist it across restarts.\")\n\n   AM4_AUTH_TOKEN = _TOKEN\n\n   def check_auth_token(request: Request) -> None:\n       \"\"\"Verify bearer token on state-mutating requests.\"\"\"\n       # Only enforce when host is non-localhost OR when token is explicitly set.\n       # For pure localhost dev, allow omission unless the env var is set.\n       auth = request.headers.get(\"authorization\", \"\")\n       expected = f\"Bearer {AM4_AUTH_TOKEN}\"\n       if not secrets.compare_digest(auth, expected):\n           raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail=\"Missing or invalid token\")\n   ```\n\n2. In `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py`, add the dependency to all POST endpoints:\n   ```python\n   from fastapi import Depends\n   from dashboard.server import check_auth_token\n\n   @router.post(\"/fleet/add\", response_class=HTMLResponse, dependencies=[Depends(check_auth_token)])\n   def api_fleet_add(...):\n       ...\n   ```\n\n   Repeat for every POST endpoint. Alternative: create a sub-router with the dependency applied once at the router level.\n\n3. Update the Jinja base template to expose the token to HTMX. Add to the `<body>` tag (this requires reading `dashboard/templates/base.html` which I haven't seen - you'll need to find the base template file and edit it):\n   ```html\n   <body hx-headers='{\"Authorization\": \"Bearer {{ auth_token }}\"}'>\n   ```\n\n4. Update the template context helper in `dashboard/server.py` or wherever `templates.TemplateResponse` is configured, to inject `auth_token` into every response context. FastAPI's Jinja2Templates supports context_processors:\n   ```python\n   def _global_context(request: Request) -> dict:\n       return {\"auth_token\": AM4_AUTH_TOKEN}\n\n   templates = Jinja2Templates(\n       directory=\"dashboard/templates\",\n       context_processors=[_global_context],\n   )\n   ```\n\n5. Document in README:\n   ```\n   ## Authentication\n\n   The dashboard uses a session token to protect mutating endpoints.\n\n   - Default (127.0.0.1): a random token is generated at startup and\n     printed to the console. The dashboard UI picks it up automatically.\n   - For LAN use or persistent sessions, set `AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN=yourtoken`\n     before starting.\n\n   Direct API calls must include `Authorization: Bearer <token>` on POST requests.\n   ```\n\n6. Commit: `git add dashboard/ README.md && git commit -m \"security(SEC-01,SEC-06): token auth on POST endpoints\"`\n\nNote: This is a meaningful change and should be tested thoroughly. If it breaks the HTMX flow, consider an alternative: SameSite=Strict cookies with a double-submit pattern. Use the `brainstorming` skill if the approach needs rethinking.",
        "testStrategy": "Start the dashboard. Confirm the token is printed at startup. Try to call a POST endpoint without the token: `curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/fleet/delete -d fleet_id=1` - should return 401. Try with the token: `curl -X POST -H \"Authorization: Bearer <token>\" http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/fleet/delete -d fleet_id=1`. Navigate the dashboard in a browser and confirm all buttons still work (HTMX picks up the token from hx-headers). Set `AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN=mytestkey` and restart, confirm it's used.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "19",
        "title": "Add recommendation breakeven: best-route variant",
        "description": "Fix the naive days_to_breakeven in fleet_recommend.py that uses average profit across all routes. Add a best-route variant.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - `days_to_breakeven = cost / avg_daily_profit` is misleading because the average blends high-profit long-haul routes with marginal short-haul ones. An aircraft can only fly ONE route at a time.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Edit `commands/fleet_recommend.py` `fleet_recommend_rows`:\n   ```python\n   # After the existing loop:\n   for tup in cur.fetchall():\n       r = dict(zip(col_names, tup, strict=True))\n       r[\"owned_qty\"] = int(r.get(\"owned_qty\") or 0)\n       avg = float(r.get(\"avg_daily_profit\") or 0)\n       best = float(r.get(\"best_daily_profit\") or 0)\n       cost = int(r.get(\"cost\") or 0)\n       r[\"days_to_breakeven_avg\"] = (\n           round(cost / avg, 1) if avg > 0 and cost > 0 else None\n       )\n       r[\"days_to_breakeven_best\"] = (\n           round(cost / best, 1) if best > 0 and cost > 0 else None\n       )\n       # Default 'days_to_breakeven' now means the best-route case -\n       # more meaningful since you'd assign the aircraft to its best route.\n       r[\"days_to_breakeven\"] = r[\"days_to_breakeven_best\"]\n       rows.append(r)\n   return rows, None\n   ```\n\n2. Update `commands/airline.py` `recommend` to print both columns:\n   ```python\n   print(\n       \"shortname\\tname\\ttype\\tcost\\towned\\troutes\\tavg_profit_day\\tbest_profit_day\\t\"\n       \"days_be_avg\\tdays_be_best\"\n   )\n   for r in rows:\n       ...\n       be_avg = r.get(\"days_to_breakeven_avg\")\n       be_best = r.get(\"days_to_breakeven_best\")\n       be_avg_out = \"\" if be_avg is None else be_avg\n       be_best_out = \"\" if be_best is None else be_best\n       print(\n           f\"{r['shortname']}\\t{r['name']}\\t{r['type']}\\t{cost}\\t{owned}\\t{r['routes']}\\t\"\n           f\"{round(avg, 2)}\\t{round(float(r.get('best_daily_profit') or 0), 2)}\\t\"\n           f\"{be_avg_out}\\t{be_best_out}\"\n       )\n   ```\n\n3. Update the dashboard Buy Next template (`dashboard/templates/partials/fleet_plan_table.html` - file I haven't seen) to show both columns. Open the file, find where `days_to_breakeven` is rendered, and duplicate to show both `days_to_breakeven_avg` and `days_to_breakeven_best`.\n\n4. Add a small note on the template: \"Days to breakeven (best route) is the lower bound - assumes the aircraft flies its single most profitable route. The avg column is higher because it averages across all viable routes.\"\n\n5. Commit: `git add commands/fleet_recommend.py commands/airline.py dashboard/templates/ && git commit -m \"feat(recommend): add best-route days_to_breakeven\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py recommend --hub KHI --budget 500000000 --top 10 --db test.db` and verify the output has both days_be_avg and days_be_best columns, with days_be_best <= days_be_avg for every row. Load the Buy Next dashboard page and verify both columns appear. Pick an aircraft with wide profitability spread and confirm the difference between avg and best is meaningful.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "20",
        "title": "Dockerfile: non-root user and multi-stage build",
        "description": "Fix SEC-12 (container runs as root) and SEC-13 (build tools in runtime image). Rewrite as multi-stage.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "4"
        ],
        "priority": "medium",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-12, SEC-13.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Replace `Dockerfile` with a multi-stage build:\n   ```dockerfile\n   # Stage 1: Build am4 C++ extension\n   FROM python:3.12-slim AS builder\n\n   RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \\\n       build-essential cmake git \\\n       && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n   WORKDIR /build\n\n   # Install into a virtualenv so we can copy the entire site-packages\n   RUN python -m venv /opt/venv\n   ENV PATH=\"/opt/venv/bin:$PATH\"\n\n   COPY requirements.txt .\n   RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip \\\n       && pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt\n\n   # Stage 2: Runtime\n   FROM python:3.12-slim AS runtime\n\n   # Minimal runtime deps only - no build tools\n   RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \\\n       libstdc++6 \\\n       && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n   # Create non-root user\n   RUN useradd --create-home --shell /bin/bash --uid 1000 appuser\n\n   # Copy the virtualenv from the builder\n   COPY --from=builder /opt/venv /opt/venv\n   ENV PATH=\"/opt/venv/bin:$PATH\"\n\n   WORKDIR /app\n   COPY --chown=appuser:appuser . .\n\n   # Ensure the data directory exists and is writable by appuser\n   RUN mkdir -p /app/data && chown -R appuser:appuser /app/data\n\n   USER appuser\n\n   EXPOSE 8000\n   CMD [\"python\", \"main.py\", \"dashboard\", \"--host\", \"0.0.0.0\"]\n   ```\n\n2. Note: The CMD passes `--host 0.0.0.0` because Docker bridge networking requires it. This is acceptable because: (a) it's the container boundary, not the host, (b) the token auth from task 18 protects the POST endpoints, (c) docker-compose should document that ports should only be published to 127.0.0.1 on the host unless LAN access is wanted.\n\n3. Update `docker-compose.yml` to bind the published port to localhost only by default:\n   ```yaml\n   services:\n     am4-ops-center:\n       build: .\n       container_name: am4-ops-center\n       ports:\n         - \"127.0.0.1:8000:8000\"  # localhost-only by default\n       volumes:\n         - .:/app\n         - am4-ops-center-data:/app/data\n       environment:\n         - AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB=/app/data/am4_data.db\n         # - AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN=set_this_if_you_want_persistent_auth\n       command: python main.py dashboard --host 0.0.0.0 --db /app/data/am4_data.db\n   volumes:\n     am4-ops-center-data:\n   ```\n\n4. Commit: `git add Dockerfile docker-compose.yml && git commit -m \"security(SEC-12,SEC-13): multi-stage docker build with non-root user\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `docker build -t am4-audit-test .` and confirm the final image size is smaller than the single-stage version (should drop by ~200MB from removing build-essential/cmake/git). Run `docker run --rm am4-audit-test id` - should show uid=1000(appuser), not root. Run `docker run --rm am4-audit-test which gcc` - should return nothing (no compilers in runtime). Run `docker compose up -d` and confirm the dashboard is reachable at http://127.0.0.1:8000/ but NOT at `http://<lan-ip>:8000/`.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "21",
        "title": "Make aircraft/airport extraction ID ranges configurable",
        "description": "Fix SEC/functional finding - hardcoded range(0, 500) for aircraft and range(0, 4500) for airports silently misses new AM4 content.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - `extractors/aircraft.py` has `for ac_id in range(0, 500)` and `extractors/airports.py` has `for ap_id in range(0, 4500)`. AM4 has ~336 aircraft and ~3900 airports today, so headroom is OK but the 500 ceiling is only 48% above current.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add config fields in `config.py`:\n   ```python\n   @dataclass\n   class UserConfig:\n       ...\n       aircraft_id_max: int = 1000\n       airport_id_max: int = 8000\n   ```\n\n2. Update `extractors/aircraft.py`:\n   ```python\n   def extract_all_aircraft(conn, cfg=None) -> list[dict]:\n       from am4.utils.aircraft import Aircraft\n       max_id = cfg.aircraft_id_max if cfg else 1000\n       ...\n       for ac_id in range(0, max_id):\n           ...\n   ```\n\n3. Same for `extractors/airports.py` with `airport_id_max`.\n\n4. Update the extraction call sites in `routes.py` to pass `cfg`.\n\n5. Add CLI flags in `main.py`:\n   ```python\n   ex.add_argument(\"--aircraft-id-max\", type=int, default=1000)\n   ex.add_argument(\"--airport-id-max\", type=int, default=8000)\n   ```\n\n6. Commit: `git add config.py extractors/ main.py && git commit -m \"feat: configurable aircraft/airport ID scan range\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py extract --hubs KHI --aircraft-id-max 200` and verify only aircraft with id < 200 are extracted. Run with the default and compare total row counts - should be >= the old count.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "22",
        "title": "Move min_runway filter from extraction time to query time",
        "description": "Fix the airports.py footgun: airports with short runways are permanently excluded from the DB during extraction, so changing fleet later can't find them.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit. Currently `extractors/airports.py` has:\n```python\nif int(ap.rwy) < min_rwy:\n    continue\n```\nThis means airports with short runways never make it into the DB. If the user later operates an aircraft with shorter runway requirements, those destinations can't be found.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Remove the min_rwy filter in `extractors/airports.py` - extract EVERY valid airport regardless of runway:\n   ```python\n   def extract_all_airports(conn: sqlite3.Connection, config: UserConfig) -> list[dict]:\n       from am4.utils.airport import Airport\n       rows: list[dict] = []\n       sql = \"\"\"...\"\"\"\n       for ap_id in range(0, config.airport_id_max):  # from task 21\n           try:\n               result = Airport.search(str(ap_id))\n               ap = result.ap\n               if not ap.valid:\n                   continue\n               # Do NOT filter by runway here - store all airports.\n               # Runway filtering happens at query time against the aircraft's min runway.\n               conn.execute(sql, (\n                   ap.id, ap.iata, ap.icao, ap.name, ap.fullname, ap.country,\n                   ap.continent, float(ap.lat), float(ap.lng), int(ap.rwy),\n                   ap.rwy_codes, int(ap.market), int(ap.hub_cost),\n               ))\n               if ap.iata:\n                   rows.append({...})\n           except Exception as exc:\n               # log via task 12\n               continue\n       conn.commit()\n       return rows\n   ```\n\n2. In `extract_routes_for_hub` (extractors/routes.py), the existing runway check is already correct - it compares `ac.rwy` to `hub.rwy` and skips mismatches. So removing the extraction-time filter doesn't break anything.\n\n3. Keep `min_runway` on UserConfig but document that it's advisory only (for hub selection), not for airport storage.\n\n4. Commit: `git add extractors/airports.py && git commit -m \"fix: extract all airports regardless of runway, filter at query time\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run a full extraction on a test DB. Count airports with `sqlite3 test.db \"SELECT COUNT(*) FROM airports WHERE rwy < 2500\"`. Previously this would be 0 (filtered out). Now it should be > 0. Run a hub extraction for KHI with an aircraft that needs only a 1500m runway and confirm short-runway destinations appear.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "23",
        "title": "CHANGELOG reconciliation and README consistency pass",
        "description": "Fix the Buy Next contradiction in CHANGELOG Unreleased section and ensure README, CHANGELOG, and code all agree.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "5",
          "19"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit - CHANGELOG Unreleased has two contradictory statements: it adds Buy Next as a new page AND says 'removed nonexistent Buy Next page'. README says 11 pages and lists Buy Next. At some point Buy Next was declared nonexistent and then reimplemented; the CHANGELOG never reconciled.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Read the current CHANGELOG.md and README.md for the dashboard page count and Buy Next mentions.\n\n2. In CHANGELOG.md, under Unreleased, delete the contradictory line about 'removed nonexistent Buy Next page' since Buy Next now exists and has been implemented.\n\n3. Add a new entry documenting the work done on this branch. Example structure:\n   ```markdown\n   ## [Unreleased]\n\n   ### Added\n   - **Authentication**: Bearer token on POST endpoints via `AM4_ROUTEMINE_TOKEN` env var (SEC-01, SEC-06).\n   - **Extract metadata**: New `extract_metadata` table persists `UserConfig` per extraction; dashboard refresh honors it instead of using hardcoded defaults.\n   - **Fleet-derived planes owned**: `total_planes_owned` now derived from `SUM(my_fleet.quantity)` unless overridden with `--planes-owned`.\n   - **Best-route breakeven**: Fleet recommendations show both `days_to_breakeven_avg` and `days_to_breakeven_best`.\n   - **Concurrency lock** on hub refresh endpoints to prevent concurrent extractions.\n   - **Configurable ID ranges**: `--aircraft-id-max` and `--airport-id-max` flags for extraction.\n\n   ### Changed\n   - **Dashboard default host** is now `127.0.0.1` (was `0.0.0.0`). Use `--host 0.0.0.0` explicitly for LAN access.\n   - **Dashboard `--reload`** is now opt-in (was unconditionally on).\n   - **Aircraft extraction** no longer filters by runway length at extract time.\n   - **Dockerfile** is now multi-stage with a non-root `appuser`.\n   - **am4 dependency** pinned to a specific commit hash instead of `msvc-fix` branch name.\n\n   ### Fixed\n   - **Schema integrity** (HIGH): `UNIQUE(origin_id, dest_id, aircraft_id)` on `route_aircraft`, `UNIQUE(shortname)` on `aircraft`, partial unique index on `airports.iata`. Extractor now uses `ON CONFLICT` upsert.\n   - **FK safety** in `replace_master_tables` (try/finally, FK-safe delete order).\n   - **TOCTOU race** (SEC-14) in fleet buy/sell - now atomic `UPDATE ... MIN(999, quantity + ?)`.\n   - **XSS** (SEC-04) in heatmap popup - now uses DOM textContent, not HTML concat.\n   - **SQL f-string** (SEC-02) for `STALE_AFTER_DAYS` - now parameterized.\n   - **Dockerfile** double-install of am4.\n   - **docker-compose** `AM4_ROUTEMINE_DB` path mismatch (`cmd_dashboard` now honors env var).\n   - **convert_csv.py** aircraft shortname mappings corrected and verified.\n   - **Per-hub commits** in `run_bulk_extraction` (no more giant-transaction memory/loss risk).\n   - **Thread safety**: per-worker `user`/`options` construction instead of shared objects.\n   - **Silent exception swallowing** in extractors now logs warnings.\n\n   ### Removed\n   - **am4_data.db.N** stray file deleted from repo.\n   - **.mcp.json** removed from tracked files; replaced with `.mcp.json.example`.\n   ```\n\n4. Update README.md:\n   - Dashboard page count is still 11.\n   - Under Authentication: add the token section from task 18.\n   - Under Prerequisites: add a line noting Node is only required for task-master-ai, not for the app itself.\n   - Under Troubleshooting: add entry for the 127.0.0.1 default (\"Can't reach from another device\").\n   - Under Upgrading: update the am4 pip install command to show the commit hash form.\n\n5. Commit: `git add CHANGELOG.md README.md && git commit -m \"docs: reconcile CHANGELOG Unreleased and update README\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Read CHANGELOG.md - verify no contradictions, all task IDs from this remediation branch are reflected. Read README.md - verify page count, authentication section, and troubleshooting table are updated. Run a spellcheck pass.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "24",
        "title": "Sanitize SQLite error messages before rendering",
        "description": "Fix SEC-18 - sqlite3.OperationalError messages are rendered directly into dashboard HTML and leak schema/path details.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-18. Multiple endpoints do `flash_err=str(exc)` with a raw OperationalError. These messages can contain table names, column names, and file paths.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add a sanitizer in `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py`:\n   ```python\n   import re\n\n   def _safe_error_message(exc: Exception, default: str = \"Database error\") -> str:\n       \"\"\"Return a sanitized error message safe for UI display.\n\n       Strips filesystem paths, preserves schema terms so users can still\n       understand common issues (missing table, locked db, etc).\n       \"\"\"\n       msg = str(exc)\n       # Strip absolute file paths\n       msg = re.sub(r\"(/[^\\s:'\\\"]+)+\", \"<path>\", msg)\n       msg = re.sub(r\"[A-Za-z]:\\\\[^\\s:'\\\"]+\", \"<path>\", msg)\n       # Cap length\n       if len(msg) > 200:\n           msg = msg[:200] + \"...\"\n       return msg or default\n   ```\n\n2. Replace every `flash_err=str(exc)` with `flash_err=_safe_error_message(exc)`. Grep for occurrences:\n   ```\n   grep -n 'flash_err=str(exc)' dashboard/routes/api_routes.py\n   ```\n\n3. Commit: `git add dashboard/routes/api_routes.py && git commit -m \"security(SEC-18): sanitize SQLite error messages in UI\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Unit-test the sanitizer: `_safe_error_message(sqlite3.OperationalError('unable to open database file: /home/user/secrets/x.db'))` should not contain `/home/user`. Trigger a real error in the dashboard (e.g., try to use a nonexistent DB path) and confirm the UI shows a scrubbed message.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "25",
        "title": "Generate pip-compile requirements.lock with hashes",
        "description": "Fix SEC-17 - no dependency hash verification.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "4"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-17. Current requirements.txt installs without hash checking.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Install pip-tools: `pip install pip-tools` (in dev env).\n\n2. Create `requirements.in` with the same content as the current requirements.txt (top-level deps only).\n\n3. Generate the locked file with hashes:\n   ```\n   pip-compile --generate-hashes --output-file=requirements.lock requirements.in\n   ```\n\n4. Update the Dockerfile to use the lock file:\n   ```dockerfile\n   COPY requirements.lock .\n   RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip \\\n       && pip install --no-cache-dir --require-hashes -r requirements.lock\n   ```\n\n5. Update the README installation section to document both files:\n   - `requirements.in` - top-level deps (edit this)\n   - `requirements.lock` - transitive deps with hashes (generated; used for install)\n   - `requirements.txt` - kept for compatibility; regenerated from requirements.in without hashes\n\n6. Add a Makefile target or script `scripts/update_deps.sh`:\n   ```bash\n   #!/usr/bin/env bash\n   set -euo pipefail\n   pip-compile --output-file=requirements.txt requirements.in\n   pip-compile --generate-hashes --output-file=requirements.lock requirements.in\n   ```\n\n7. Commit: `git add requirements.in requirements.lock scripts/update_deps.sh Dockerfile README.md && git commit -m \"security(SEC-17): pip-compile lock with hashes\"`\n\nNote: The am4 Git URL dependency can't have a hash via pip-compile because it's a direct URL. Document this as an exception - the commit hash pin from task 4 provides the integrity guarantee for am4 specifically.",
        "testStrategy": "Run `docker build -t am4-audit-test .` and confirm hash verification is active (any tampered package would fail). Inspect requirements.lock and verify every line has a `--hash=sha256:...` entry except am4.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "26",
        "title": "Add CLI backup subcommand",
        "description": "Fix SEC-15 - no DB backup mechanism. Add a simple backup CLI that uses SQLite's online backup API.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "1"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: SEC-15. Currently no way to back up the SQLite DB. SQLite's online backup API can snapshot a DB even while the dashboard is reading from it.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Add `cmd_backup` in `main.py`:\n   ```python\n   def cmd_backup(args: argparse.Namespace) -> None:\n       import datetime\n       from database.schema import get_connection\n       src = Path(args.db)\n       if not src.exists():\n           print(f\"Error: source DB not found: {src}\", file=sys.stderr)\n           sys.exit(2)\n       ts = datetime.datetime.now(datetime.timezone.utc).strftime(\"%Y%m%dT%H%M%SZ\")\n       dst_dir = Path(args.output or \"./backups\")\n       dst_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n       dst = dst_dir / f\"{src.stem}_{ts}.db\"\n       src_conn = get_connection(str(src))\n       dst_conn = sqlite3.connect(str(dst))\n       with dst_conn:\n           src_conn.backup(dst_conn)\n       src_conn.close()\n       dst_conn.close()\n       size_mb = dst.stat().st_size / (1024 * 1024)\n       print(f\"Backup written to {dst} ({size_mb:.1f} MB)\")\n   ```\n\n2. Register the subparser:\n   ```python\n   bk = sub.add_parser(\"backup\", help=\"Snapshot the SQLite DB to a timestamped file\")\n   bk.add_argument(\"--db\", type=str, default=\"am4_data.db\")\n   bk.add_argument(\"--output\", type=str, default=\"./backups\", help=\"Output directory\")\n   bk.set_defaults(func=cmd_backup)\n   ```\n\n3. Update `.gitignore` to exclude `backups/` (the new `*.db*` pattern from task 2 already handles the backup files themselves, but add the directory for clarity).\n\n4. Commit: `git add main.py .gitignore && git commit -m \"feat: backup subcommand using SQLite online backup API\"`",
        "testStrategy": "Run `python main.py backup --db am4_data.db` - should create `./backups/am4_data_<timestamp>.db`. Confirm the backup file is readable: `sqlite3 backups/am4_data_*.db \"SELECT COUNT(*) FROM route_aircraft\"` should return a sensible number. Run backup while the dashboard is running and confirm it completes without locking errors.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
      {
        "id": "27",
        "title": "Split api_routes.py into per-domain modules",
        "description": "Refactor the 2,122-line api_routes.py into focused modules. This is a low-risk refactor that improves maintainability.",
        "status": "done",
        "dependencies": [
          "5",
          "8",
          "15",
          "16",
          "17",
          "18",
          "24"
        ],
        "priority": "low",
        "details": "Findings: Deep-dive audit item. api_routes.py is 2,122 lines and mixes hub explorer, aircraft, route analyzer, fleet CRUD, routes CRUD, hub manager, contributions, heatmap, stats, and charts in one file.\n\nThis task depends on all the other api_routes.py changes completing first, to avoid merge conflicts.\n\nSteps:\n\n1. Create a new directory structure:\n   ```\n   dashboard/routes/api/\n   ├── __init__.py   (combines all sub-routers)\n   ├── shared.py     (sort allowlists, helpers, error sanitizer, lock)\n   ├── analytics.py  (hub-routes, hub-summary, hub-chart, aircraft-*, route-*, chart/*)\n   ├── fleet.py      (fleet/*)\n   ├── routes.py     (routes/*, route-exists, routes/pair-coverage) - note name conflict, consider 'my_routes.py'\n   ├── hubs.py       (hubs/*)\n   ├── recommendations.py  (fleet-plan, contributions, heatmap-*)\n   └── meta.py       (stats, search/*)\n   ```\n\n2. Each module defines its own `APIRouter()` with the same `/api` prefix.\n\n3. `dashboard/routes/api/__init__.py` imports and combines:\n   ```python\n   from fastapi import APIRouter\n   from . import analytics, fleet, my_routes, hubs, recommendations, meta\n\n   router = APIRouter(prefix=\"/api\", tags=[\"api\"])\n   router.include_router(analytics.router)\n   router.include_router(fleet.router)\n   router.include_router(my_routes.router)\n   router.include_router(hubs.router)\n   router.include_router(recommendations.router)\n   router.include_router(meta.router)\n   ```\n\n   Note: nested include_router with shared prefix needs care. An alternative is for each sub-module to define its own prefix-free router and the parent to add the prefix.\n\n4. Move the shared helpers (`_hub_order`, `_ac_order`, `_route_order`, `_contrib_order`, `_hub_filter_sql`, `_safe_field_id`, `_stale_cutoff_iso`, `_safe_error_message`, `_EXTRACTION_LOCK`, sort allowlists) to `shared.py`.\n\n5. Update imports in `dashboard/server.py` to import from the new location. The existing `from dashboard.routes.api_routes import router` becomes `from dashboard.routes.api import router`.\n\n6. Delete the old `dashboard/routes/api_routes.py`.\n\n7. Run the dashboard and click through every page to verify routing still works.\n\n8. Commit: `git add dashboard/ && git commit -m \"refactor: split api_routes.py into per-domain modules\"`\n\nSuperpowers: Use `requesting-code-review` after this task - it's a big refactor that's easy to get wrong (missed imports, broken routes). Have a second review pass before committing.",
        "testStrategy": "Start the dashboard and manually visit every page: /, /hub-explorer, /aircraft, /route-analyzer, /fleet-planner, /buy-next, /my-fleet, /my-routes, /my-hubs, /contributions, /heatmap. Every HTMX fragment must load. Every POST action (buy, sell, add fleet, add route, refresh hub) must work. Run `python -m pytest tests/` if tests exist.",
        "subtasks": []
      },
